***

**1. Express $$ C_{geom} $$ explicitly as a function.**  
Define it parametrically to highlight its dependence on planetary geometry:
$$
C_{geom} = f(\Theta, \rho(r), R, \Omega, e)
$$
where  
- $$ \Theta $$: axial tilt  
- $$ \rho(r) $$: radial density distribution  
- $$ R $$: mean planetary radius  
- $$ \Omega $$: angular velocity  
- $$ e $$: orbital eccentricity  

This shows how $$ C_{geom} $$ encodes the integrated geometry and mass anisotropy of the body.

***

**2. Provide a general expression for cross-planet scaling.**  
Illustrate universality through a dimensionless relation:
$$
\frac{S_{planet}}{S_{Earth}} = 
\frac{(1 - C_{geom,planet}) \, \tau_{G,planet} \, M_{A,planet}}{(1 - C_{geom,Earth}) \, \tau_{G,Earth} \, M_{A,Earth}} 
+ \frac{\dot{I}_{planet}}{\dot{I}_{Earth}}
$$
This allows normalized comparison across planetary bodies (e.g., applying Earth-derived calibration constants to Mars or Titan).

